(6) Possible alignment opportunities between funded programs and current and
projected workforce shortages in Louisiana.
(7) Recommendations for more efficient coordination between secondary education,
postsecondary institutions, and workforce development programs.
(8) Recommendations for improving program accessibility, efficiency, and
alignment with the workforce needs of employers and the education and training needs of
students.
(9) Outcomes of program participants disaggregated by age, including but not
limited to participants under the age of twenty-one.
(10) Comparative analysis of similarly situated individuals who did not receive
program funding, including individuals of comparable age, educational attainment, and
workforce status, in order to assess differences in employment, earnings, and career
progression associated with participation in the M.J. Foster Promise Program and the TOPS-
Tech Award.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the Board of Regents shall provide a
comparative analysis of all state-funded financial aid programs including an evaluation of
any gaps in financial support that create barriers to participant access.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the Board of Regents shall submit a written
report of its findings and recommendations to the House Committee on Education, the House
Committee on Labor and Industrial Relations, and the House Committee on Appropriations,
not later than February 15, 2027.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that a copy of this Resolution be transmitted to the
commissioner of higher education, the secretary of Louisiana Works, the state
superintendent of education, the president of the Louisiana Community and Technical
College System, the executive director of the Kathleen Babineaux Blanco Public Policy
Center, the chair of the Board of Supervisors of Louisiana State University and Agricultural
and Mechanical College, and the chair of the Board of Supervisors of Southern University
and Agricultural and Mechanical College.
